	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Ahh, the lava rain.  Another lousy excuse for an AE spell.  I still question why these spells were even put in the game in the first place.  <BR>
<BR>
200 mana to cast<BR>
128 damage per wave, up to 3 waves against solo mobs.  Or will hit a max of 4 mobs once for 128.<BR>
<BR>
Ahh, but this is a lingering rain spell!  And guess what!  We wizies aren't immune to its effects.  Result?  If you cast it and then run through it, YOU take damage!  <BR>
<BR>
The BEST use for this spell that I can figure is when there are two mobs and only two mobs.  The spell has the potential to hit each mob twice max for 128 each wave, or 256 theoretical damage per mob.  Unfortunatly, it gets a lot of full resists, and plenty of partial resists.  Rarely have I seen it hit any single mob 3 times for 128 each wave.  <BR>
<BR>
As a note to having root stick, umm, the chances of that happening are slim to none.  By the time you can cast this spell, you also realize that if you root a mob, it gets a save against the root each time it is cast on.  This spell give the mob 3 chances to break root.  Simply put, if the root holds AND you hit 3 times for max damage, you are one lucky wiz.  <BR>
<BR>
I have tested this spell far too many times (50+ times in the name of science) and have yet to find an application where I prefer this spell over Circle of force, or Thunderclap.  Further, it is not as mana efficient as is Ice Shock.  <BR>
<BR>
As far as I can tell, this is the Wiz equivelent of a DOT.  It sux nonetheless.  <BR>
<BR>
Praxis  L35 wiz, Rodcet Nife
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
